File: Miners walk past the entrance of the Sibanye-Stillwater platinum mine in Marikana, near Rustenburg. AFP/Michele Spatari JOHANNESBURG - Mineworkers will down tools at Sibanye-Stillwater's gold operations on Wednesday evening. Unions Amcu and NUM served the country's largest mining employer with a strike notice yesterday. READ: Sibanye-Stillwater Strike | NUM threatens to strike The action comes after months of prolonged wage talks between Sibanye and workers deadlocked. Unions are demanding a pay increase of R1,000 per month over the next three years. READ: Unions vote to down tools at Sibanye-Stillwater This is similar to the amount Sibanye's rival Harmony Gold agreed to pay workers last year. Sibanye is offering R700 for category 4 to 8 workers, saying it cannot afford higher increases. The gold price is now hovering above $2,000 an ounce.